issue.title: get InvalidCastException when I use [Inject]IAccessTokenProvider
issue.body:
I have a Blazor project.I'm trying to distribute it two ways: as WASM and Blazor server. So in the WASM code, I tried to be compatible with both. This is the code where I found the problem. My version is AspNet core 7.

` [Inject]
 public required IAccessTokenProvider TokenProvider { get; set; }
`

It works fine with Blazor WASM. But when I try to run it as Blazor server, I get an exception.

**_InvalidCastException: Unable to cast object of type 'Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Server.ServerAuthenticationStateProvider' to type 'Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly.Authentication.IAccessTokenProvider'._**

This means that Blazor server injected a ServerAuthenticationStateProvider into this property.According to the documentation below, this class is for server-side Blazor.
[https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.components.server.serverauthenticationstateprovider?view=aspnetcore-7.0](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.components.server.serverauthenticationstateprovider?view=aspnetcore-7.0)
Since it cannot be converted to an instance of IAccessTokenProvider, how should I handle this error that occurs during IAccessTokenProvider injection?

I also tried searching for ServerAuthenticationStateProvider but found no sample code available. And, the "Microsoft.AspNetCore.App.Ref v7.0.5" Nuget package to which this class belongs cannot be installed into my project.

Does anyone know how to solve this problem? Make the injection of IAccessTokenProvider error-free in server-side Blazor and obtain a usable object instance

issue.title: MapBlazorHub configuration in NET8 throws a `The request matched multiple endpoints` exception
issue.body:
### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the existing issues

### Describe the bug

We are working on migrating our blazor server application from NET6 to NET8 (to solve some auth issues we were having) and the guide advised this of us: 

```diff
- app.MapBlazorHub();
+ app.MapRazorComponents<App>()
+   .AddInteractiveServerRenderMode()
```

And we didn't know where to move the endpoint configuration to, which was previously being done in `MapBlazorHub`. Our previous call looked like this: 

```csharp
endpoints.MapBlazorHub(config =>
{
    config.CloseOnAuthenticationExpiration = true;
});
```

This was clarified by @guardrex in https://github.com/dotnet/AspNetCore.Docs/issues/30843 where it was asked for us to place the `MapBlazorHub` call after the call to `MapRazorComponents ... AddInteractiveServerRenderMode` block. Which we did.

However, after doing this, we got the following exception: 

```
Microsoft.AspNetCore.Routing.Matching.AmbiguousMatchException: The request matched multiple endpoints. Matches: Blazor initializers
```

And blazor doesn't seem to boot up on the browser.

### Expected Behavior

Expectation is as follows: 

- Project is upgraded to NET8 
- Server closes the connection when authentication expires as in NET6

milestone.description: This milestone tracks work that should happen by the .NET 8 GA, which requires no code / functional changes to the framework. Most of the work that will happen in this milestone is documentation and samples.

issue.body:
Hi.
In trying to add roles to my Blazor app.

```
builder.Services.AddIdentityCore<ApplicationUser>(options => options.SignIn.RequireConfirmedAccount = true)
    .AddEntityFrameworkStores<ApplicationDbContext>()
    .AddSignInManager()
    .AddRoles<IdentityRole>()
    .AddDefaultTokenProviders();`
```
    
I added  `.AddRoles<IdentityRole>()` to the "Out of the box" template "dotnet new blazor -au Individual"
    
Exception thrown: 'System.AggregateException' in Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection.dll
    
Am I missing something...
    
Regards,
Dean

issue.title: ASP .NET 8 RC2 Routing & UseStaticFiles
issue.body:
### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the existing issues

### Describe the bug

This is the same bug as #50707 , except when using an Additional Assembly. That is, with an optional parameter in the route, the app is unusable, because all requests to static assets get routed the to the blazor page, not the static asset.

Changing the page directive from `@page "/{PageName?}"` to `@page "/"` fixes the issue.

I have tried this on rc2 and nightly.



### Steps To Reproduce

repository here - [https://github.com/OpenEnergyGroup/BlazorApp4](https://github.com/OpenEnergyGroup/BlazorApp4)

### .NET Version

8.0.100-rtm.23526.1

comment.body:
Hi - thanks very much - is it the expected design that static files are lower down in priority than optional routes? That's not be behaviour we see with our 7.0 app, where all static files are matched before trying to match a route.

You're fix does work though (although wouldn't, I think, if you had an extensionless file) - I suggest this issue could be added to breaking changes.

issue.title: In .NET 8 Blazor Web App, FontAwsome icons not displayed when navigating to a page
issue.body: ### Is there an existing issue for this? - [X] I have searched the existing issues ### Describe the bug FontAwesome icons are not displayed when navigating to a page. ### Expected Behavior Icons should be displayed, as is the case with the .NET 7 version. ### Steps To Reproduce Using Visual Studio Community 2022 Preview v 17.8.0 5.0: - Create new Blazor Web App project keeping all default options (I tried different interactivity modes, same issue). - In the App.razor file add a line in the section (XXXXXXXXX is the FontAwesome free kit id): `` - In the NavMenu.razor file or the Counter.razor file, add an icon: `` - Run the application When the page is initialy displayed or the whole page is refreshed (F5), the icon is displayed. But when you navigate to a new page, using a nav item for example, FontAwesome icons are not displayed. ### Exceptions (if any) _No response_ ### .NET Version 8.0.100-rc.2.23502.2 ### Anything else? _No response_

issue.title: Unsure how to inject HttpClient for InteractiveAuto render mode (RC2)

milestone.title: .NET 8: Documentation
milestone.description: This milestone tracks work that should happen by the .NET 8 GA, which requires no code / functional changes to the framework. Most of the work that will happen in this milestone is documentation and samples.

issue.body:
I'm not sure if this is a problem in RC2 or if I'm just too new to InteractiveAuto render mode.

I have a component in the client project which calls back to the server for its api calls since the actual call to the third party api needs to be on the server (auth tokens, secrets, and the like).

Per the documentation in [Call a web API in Blazor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/call-web-api?view=aspnetcore-8.0&pivots=webassembly#call-web-api-example) on the WebAssembly pivot, it says I can register an HttpClient back to the base address with:

`builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri(builder.HostEnvironment.BaseAddress) });`

Then I wrote the component to make the call back to localhost... then the server project happens to have a minimal api route to make the "real" call.

This has worked fine as long as I don't put the component on the home page.  What I observe happening is that if I place the component on any "secondary page" and let the home page load, the wasm assembly must be streamed down and a breakpoint on the above line fires.

If I put it on the home page, that breakpoint doesn't fire, but the component is rendered.  In OnInitializeAsync() it tries to use the HttpClient to call home but BaseAddress wasn't set, so it fails.

Should components intended to be used with InteractiveAuto look to a different part of the lifecycle?

I think another option was to also register an HttpClient in the server Program.cs, but I can't figure out how to do this so that it is picked up in the initial render (perhaps it is using Blazor Server for that or prerendering... it's auto after all).

I'm not sure this is a bug or I'm ahead of the curve on the documentation for Auto modes. I can provide a sample if this behavior seems like a potential bug.

Note: All components and pages are in the Client project.  I am experimenting with the experience for global InteractiveAuto.  I only moved Error.razor to server side per known RC2 issue.

comment.body: Why not use the IHttpClientFactory with a named HttpClient to your third party api?

issue.title: Customize location of JavascriptInitializer javascript

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: This issue represents an ask for new feature or an enhancement to an existing one

issue.body:
### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the existing issues

### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

App automatically downloads javascript initializers from `_content/*/*.lib.module.js`, in example `_content/Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.CustomElements/Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.CustomElements.lib.module.js`. This behavior is well documented [here](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/fundamentals/startup?view=aspnetcore-7.0). Path of this initializer is automatically prefixed by `document.baseURI`.

My app is part of bigger app created in microfrontend fashion and I need to load my scripts from `/my-product` path. App base path is default ('/'), and I cannot change it, as it would affect all products.
Blazor attempts to load all files from `_content/*/*.lib.module.js`, however it should load them from /my-product/_content/*/*.lib.module.js`, as I am unable to host it in root directory.

### Describe the solution you'd like

Ability to customize location of initializers, i.e. configure prefix which will be applied to all initializers instead of `document.baseURI`, or function similar to `loadBootResource` which can be passed to `Blazor.start`.

### Additional context

May be related to https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/38690, however I cannot set base path

comment.body: Blazor app too much relies on document.baseURI, it makes CustomElements harder to use, as embeded Blazor app won't always share same root path as its host website

Enhances fallback testing of the <link> element by checking css pseudo-elements

## Description

Current implementation uses a small Javascript function to test if a CDN load of a resource has been successful by checking if a specified css element is present after the load. This does not work when the resource is a css that consists entirely of pseudo-elements (i.e. items with ::before or ::after suffixes).

This change adds a second script that is identical to the current one, but takes the name of the pseudo-element as an additional parameter, and passes it to the getComputedStyle function.

The changes to the actual code are minimal. I made them for 100% backward compatibility: when the newly added `asp-fallback-test-pseudo-element` attribute is not present, the JavaScript function generated by the tag helper remain the same as in the current code.

The majority of the changes in this pull request are in the unit test code and the test data. Since the new attribute is optional, I made copies of all unit tests in which the new attribute is relevant, and adjusted the generated code to match the new functionality.

Fixes #38146
